headline: Global Stocks Trounce the S&P 500 in Trump’s Chaotic First Year
summary: Measured against stock markets from Tokyo to Frankfurt to financial capitals across the developing world, though, the verdict on Trump’s return to the White House is decidedly less triumphal.  In fact, equities worldwide — once the US is excluded — have risen around 30% since he took office a year ago, roughly double the S&P 500’s gain, according to MSCI’s index.  Trump’s comparison with his predecessors is no better: As far as the S&P 500 goes, the first-year gain under Trump clocks in as only the ninth best start to a term since World War II, according to CFRA.
